On Friday 05 November 2004 05:51, timotius_pamungkas wrote:
&gt; Hi all,
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;m new in JUnit and want to ask a question. Suppose I have a
&gt; MyRectangle class with this method :
&gt;
&gt; public void setWidth(int w) throws IllegalArgumentException {
&gt;     if (w &lt; 1) {
&gt;         throw new IllegalArgumentException();
&gt;     }
&gt;     width = w;
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; and this junit method :
&gt;
&gt; public void testSetWidth() {
&gt;     MyRectangle rect = new MyRectangle();
&gt;
&gt;     Assert.assertNotNull(rect);
&gt;     rect.setWidth(-5);
&gt;     Assert.assertEquals(-5, rect.getWidth());
&gt;     rect.setWidth(4);
&gt;     Assert.assertEquals(4, rect.getWidth());
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; When I call rect.setWidth(-5), it should be throw an exception, and
&gt; it really throw an exception. The problem is, my test stop at that
&gt; point, so rect.setWidtt(4) never executed. But all I need is it
&gt; really throw an exception or not. If it&#39;s throws an exception, that
&gt; means the method is correct, and the JUnit should continue with next
&gt; test. But if it didn&#39;t throw any exception, that means the code is
&gt; wrong (maybe I forget to check the parapmeter), so if this happen, my
&gt; Junit will stop. How can i create this kind of test?

Don&#39;t try. Write two tests.

Write a test to ensure that correct width-setting works:

    public void testValidWidthSetting()
        {
        MyRectangle rect = new MyRectangle();
        rect.setWidth( 17 );
        assertEquals( 17, rect.getWidth() );
        }

[You *don&#39;t* need to check `rect` is non-null; if it is, the
 JVM is broken; all bets are off, anyway.]

And another to check that the exception gets thrown:

    public void testInvalidWidthException()
        {
        MyRectangle rect = new MyRectangle();
        try { rect.setWidth( -42 ); fail( &quot;illegal width should be detected&quot; ); }
        catch (IllegalArgumentException e) { /* yes, nothing */ }
        }

And if a lot of your tests start with 

        MyRectangle rect = new MyRectangle();

make it a fixture of your TestCase.

